<TITLE> Polish PM Kaczynski says to resign </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 WARSAW, Oct 24 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Poland's conservative Prime Minister Jaroslaw Kaczynski said on Wednesday he would resign on Nov. 5 after losing a parliamentary election, allowing centre-right opposition leader Donald Tusk to succeed him. Tusk began talks on forming a coalition with a centrist party after the election victory on Sunday of his Civic Platform, which was welcomed by markets after two years of turbulent rule by Kaczynski and his twin brother. The prime minister and President Lech Kaczynski, still in office until at least 2010, have ruled during a boom in central Europe's biggest economy but were caught up in almost constant political infighting and quarrels with EU partners. Kaczynski said he would resign on Nov. 5, when the new parliament sits for the first time. He reiterated that his Law and Justice party would be a strong opposition. "This will be a tough opposition but an opposition that takes into account the interests of the state," he said, adding that he expected the new parliament to complete its four-year term. His coalition fell apart after two years in bitter squabbling over a corruption investigation. Ahead of coalition talks with the Peasants Party (PSL), Tusk sketched out plans for freeing up the economy. He said priorities were to cut bureaucracy, limit the role of officials over state-controlled firms and discuss a new flat rate of income tax. "I will be persuading PSL to limit the presence of politicians in the economy," Tusk told Polish television TVN24. "We're not going to decide today who gets which ministries, but we want to set common principles and discuss priorities," Tusk said, adding that he expected the coalition talks to be "friendly and fas
